Analysis for WSN abstract

M Fisher

2022-10-11

Description

Summarize the following from the sequencing run:

  1. Prey diversity:
  1. alpha diversity - what proportion of reads were identified down to genus or species?
  2. beta diversity - What was the unique number of taxa identified per site/month? per site?
  3. nMDS
  1. Prey identification:
  1. what proportion of crab from each site had eaten a given phylum / class?


For this script, I’m going to remove identifications that with too little taxonomic depth (information at family or below is missing), and IDs that may have made it through filtering (rank is specific but all other taxonomic info is missing)

dat.filter <- dat %>%
  filter (rank %in% c("family","species","genus")) %>%
  filter (!(is.na(phylum) & is.na(class) & is.na(family) & is.na(order) & is.na(genus)))


And let’s check the number of crab / site with 1,2 and 3 replicates retained.

Prey Diversity

Alpha div

What is the species richness (\(\alpha\) diversity) at each site, for species? Richness per crab is simply the species richness / total crab from site.

## # A tibble: 4 x 4
##   Site      ncrab richness richness.per.crab
##   <chr>     <int>    <int>             <dbl>
## 1 CLAY         10       50              5   
## 2 KAY          11       40              3.64
## 3 KAY-shell     6       28              4.67
## 4 MARPT         2       11              5.5


What is the species richness (\(\alpha\) diversity) at each site, for genus?

## # A tibble: 4 x 4
##   Site      ncrab richness richness.per.crab
##   <chr>     <int>    <int>             <dbl>
## 1 CLAY         10       56              5.6 
## 2 KAY          11       46              4.18
## 3 KAY-shell     6       34              5.67
## 4 MARPT         2       14              7


Beta div

What is the species richness (\(\beta\) diversity) for species? (the ratio between regional and local species diversity) Note that for this sequencing run only, I include Hemigrapsus sp and Mya sp to species level.

##           1         2         3
## 2 0.4571429                    
## 3 0.7173913 0.7750000          
## 4 0.8867925 0.9024390 0.7777778
## [1] "KAY"       "KAY-shell" "CLAY"      "MARPT"

The greater the similarity in community composition between multiple communities, the lower the value of β-diversity for that set of communities.

Beta diversity is greater between distant sites (Kayak Point v. Clayton Beach v. March Point) than it is between neighboring sites (Kayak Point eelgrass v. shell).
